## Social and Political Challenges

- Public acceptance of renewable energy is generally high, with surveys showing **over 80% support** in many countries ([Brown et al., 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S136403211830618X)).

- Challenges include **land use conflicts**, **grid infrastructure siting**, and **transition management** for workers in fossil fuel industries ([Jacobson et al., 2017](https://www.cell.com/joule/fulltext/S2542-4351(17)30235-7)).

- Political will and **coordinated policy frameworks** are critical to accelerate deployment and overcome inertia ([LUT/EWG, 2019](https://physicsworld.com/a/a-global-100-renewable-energy-system/)).

---

## Critiques and Limitations

- Some researchers argue that **storage technologies and grid integration at scale remain unproven** or economically challenging ([Heard et al., 2017](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1364032117303837)).

- Concerns about **material scarcity**, **rare earth elements**, and **energy return on investment** are ongoing ([García-Olivares et al., 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0196890418300226)).

- Nuclear energy proponents criticize the exclusion of nuclear and carbon capture technologies in some renewable scenarios as **limiting viable options** ([Heard et al., 2017](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1364032117303837)).

---

## Conclusion and Opinion

Based on the comprehensive evidence from multiple peer-reviewed studies and expert analyses, **it is technically and economically feasible to power the world with 100% renewable energy by 2050**. The key enablers include:

- Massive expansion of **wind and solar power**, which together can supply over 85% of primary energy.

- **Electrification of all sectors**, including transport and heating, coupled with efficient energy use.

- Deployment of **energy storage technologies** and grid infrastructure upgrades to ensure reliability.

- **Material resource management** and technological innovation to address critical supply constraints.

However, **feasibility alone does not guarantee realization**. The transition requires:

- Strong political commitment and coordinated global policy frameworks.

- Social acceptance and just transition strategies for affected workers and communities.

- Continued technological innovation and cost reductions.

- Addressing economic and infrastructural challenges, especially in developing countries.

In my informed opinion, the **transition to 100% renewable energy is not only feasible but imperative** to meet climate goals and ensure sustainable development. While challenges remain, the convergence of technological maturity, economic competitiveness, and social support provides a robust foundation for this transformation. Policymakers and stakeholders should prioritize enabling conditions and investments to accelerate this transition, rather than deferring to uncertain or controversial alternatives.

